ANC officials are contradicting each other, over whether the party has decided to expand the mandate of the South African Reserve Bank. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - ANC leaders appear to be sending mixed messages on the issue of the mandate of the South African Reserve Bank. ANC Secretary-General Ace Magashule on Tuesday addressed a media briefing following the NEC's three-day lekgotla. Magashule said the ANC NEC had agreed to expand the mandate of the South African Reserve Bank. According to Magashule, the party wants the Reserve Bank to also focus on economic growth and employment. READ: ANC agrees to expand mandate of SARB “The NEC lekgotla also agreed to expand the mandate of the SARB beyond price stability to include growth and employment. You don’t need to change the Constitution for that… It will operate the way it's operating,” he said. However, Finance Minister Tito Mboweni said on Twitter that “Government sets the mandate for the SARB.” ANC’s economic transformation head, Enoch Godongwana said the ANC's Lekgotla is not a decision-making body. He was speaking with SAFM's Stephen Grootes. “...The Lekgotla is not decision making. Lekgotla makes decisions and makes a recommendation to the National Executive Committee.” Godongwana said not even the ANC's highest decision body, the NEC could overturn a conference's resolution. Did you know?
